<HEADLINE>
19% OF TAIWAN PEOPLE HAVE FOOD ALLERGIES: SURVEY
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  April 28 (CNA) 04/28/07  16:49:32 (By Y.F. Low)
</P>
<P>
As many as 19 percent of people in Taiwan are allergic to certain
kinds of food, according to the results of a survey released
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, released during an annual meeting of the Taiwan
Pediatric Association held in Taipei, was conducted by the Taipei
Veterans General Hospital, the Shin Kong Wu Ho Su Memorial
Hospital, the Tri-Service General Hospital, the Taichung Veterans
General Hospital, the Kaohsiung General Hospital and the Tzu-chi
Buddhist General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
Among the more-than 30,000 people surveyed by the hospitals, 13
percent of those 0-3 years of age, 20 percent of those 6-12 years
of age and 17 percent of adults have food allergies, the survey
shows.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that chicken, eggs, milk, mangoes and peanuts,
as well as shellfish such as crabs, clams and shrimps, are the
most common kinds of allergy-causing foods.
</P>
<P>
There are also people who are allergic to cod and cuttlefish,
according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
Yao Tzung-chieh,  a pediatrician  at Chang Gung Children's
Hospital, noted that symptoms of food allergies can include itchy
skin, rashes, abdominal pain and diarrhea, and he urged people
who display the symptoms but have had no idea of the source of
their allergies to receive allergy tests, available at most
hospitals.
</P>
